===Etymology===
Named after the inventor, German chemist Richard Erlenmeyer, who created it in 1861.

===Noun===
{{en-noun|head=[[w:Richard August Carl Emil Erlenmeyer|Erlenmeyer]] [[flask]]}}

# {{label|en|chemistry}} A glass [[laboratory]] flask of a conical profile with a narrow tubular neck and a flat bottom, used to manipulate solutions, or to carry out [[titration]]s.
#* '''2006''', Thomas Pynchon, ''Against the Day'', Vintage 2007, p. 265:
#*: An assistant arrived with a wheeled cart bearing coffee in an '''Erlenmeyer flask''', cups, and a plate of strange muffins.

